# Sample Output

## Step 1: Imagine the Scene in Vivid Detail

### As an Observer

It starts with hunger. Not just a passing hunger from missing a meal, but a deep, gnawing hunger that lasts for weeks and months. The fields outside Bethlehem—normally golden with wheat and barley—are bare. Families are rationing what little grain they have left. Mothers hush crying children with watered-down meals, hoping tomorrow will bring relief.

Naomi's family can't wait any longer. They pack up what they can—clothes, tools, maybe some dried food—and set out on foot, leaving behind everything familiar. It's a hard road to Moab, over hills and dry land, past the Jordan River. They aren't the only ones leaving, but every step away from home feels heavier.

Naomi glances back at Bethlehem. It's her birthplace. The land of her people. The place where she expected to grow old. Now she walks into the unknown.

### As Naomi

You tell yourself this will be temporary. You're just going until the famine ends. But the moment you step into Moab, everything feels different. The language is strange. The customs don't match what you grew up with. You feel the eyes of the Moabites on you—some curious, some cold.

Then, just when you think you're settling in, your husband, Elimelek, dies. You wake up one morning, and he's gone. The man you built your life with, the one who carried the weight of your family's survival, is no longer beside you. But you still have your sons, Mahlon and Kilion. They are your last tie to the future.

You hope that marriage will anchor them. Mahlon marries Ruth, and Kilion marries Orpah, both Moabite women. It isn't what you once imagined for them. You had always pictured them marrying Israelite women, raising their children in the traditions of your people, carrying on the faith of your ancestors. But this is Moab. Nothing has gone as you expected, and at least your sons are not alone. You try to hold on to that hope.

Then, after ten years, both Mahlon and Kilion die. First, one son is gone, and then the other. Orpah loses her husband, Kilion. Ruth loses her husband, Mahlon. And you—Naomi—lose everything.

You sit in the silence of a home that once held laughter and plans for the future. The grief is suffocating. There is no husband, no sons—only you, Naomi, a foreigner in a land that never truly became home.

### As Ruth

You remember the first time you saw Naomi. She looked different from the women of Moab—her clothes, her speech, the way she carried herself. She had the weight of a woman who had seen loss but still had strength.

When you married Mahlon, you stepped into a family that was different from yours. You had grown up with Moabite customs, Moabite gods, a way of life that had always felt familiar. But Naomi's world was shaped by something else—her faith, her traditions, her belief in a God who was unlike any you had known.

Then came the worst news. First, Orpah's husband, Kilion, dies. Then, your own husband, Mahlon, is gone too. Just like that, Naomi loses everything—her last two sons, her last ties to security. And suddenly, you and Orpah do too. The life you thought you were building disappears in an instant.

You look at Naomi, sitting in silence, staring at nothing. The woman who once spoke with warmth now carries only sorrow. How do you comfort someone who has lost so much? And what will become of you now?

## Step 2: Imagine the Scene in Cultural Context

Bethlehem, the "house of bread," is empty of food. Some must have wondered—has God abandoned us?

Leaving Bethlehem for Moab was not an easy decision. Moab and Israel had a complicated history. The Moabites were distant relatives, descended from Lot, but they had been enemies as often as they were neighbors. Israelites didn't usually trust Moabites, and Moabites didn't usually welcome Israelites.

But desperate times lead people to desperate choices. Did the people of Moab treat Naomi's family with suspicion? Did they struggle to make a place for themselves? The text doesn't say, but we can imagine the challenge of being outsiders in a foreign land.

And then there's Naomi's loss. In her culture, a woman's security came through her husband and sons. With them gone, she had no land, no rights, no clear future. She was a widow in a world that did not offer many options to widows.

She had come to Moab with hope. Now, she had nothing.

## Step 3: Imagine the Scene in Emotional and Spiritual Context

Naomi left Bethlehem full—full of family, full of possibility. Now she is empty.

Did she wonder if God was punishing her? Did she regret leaving Bethlehem in the first place? She has no answers, only grief.

And yet, in all this sorrow, God is still present. His name is not mentioned in these verses, but He is working behind the scenes. In her darkest moment, Naomi is not truly alone.

We've all faced moments where life has unraveled. Maybe you've had a season where everything you depended on was suddenly gone—a job, a home, a relationship, a sense of security. Like Naomi, you might have wondered where God was in it all.

But the story isn't over yet.

## Step 4: Connect the Scene to Ourselves

Have you ever had to leave home, not knowing if you'd ever return?

Have you ever faced a loss so deep that the future felt empty?

Maybe, like Naomi, you've felt the ache of prayers that seem unanswered. Maybe you've stood at a crossroads, unsure where to go next.

This passage doesn't tie everything up neatly. Naomi is still grieving. She doesn't have a plan yet. But in the midst of her loss, God is preparing something she can't yet see.

Ruth, standing beside her, will become part of that plan. Even though Naomi doesn't realize it yet, hope is already growing in her story.

## Step 5: Name the Scene

### Title
*When Everything Falls Apart*

### Summary
This is a story of loss, but not the end of the story. Naomi's world crumbles, but God is still present, working in ways she cannot yet understand.

### Challenge/Encouragement
Life doesn't always go as planned. We all face famine seasons—times of emptiness, loss, and uncertainty. But God's work isn't always obvious in the moment. Even in sorrow, even in silence, He is still at work.

Maybe your story feels like Naomi's right now—empty, uncertain, broken. If so, hold on. The story isn't over yet.
